Thank you for your interest in Sacramento State!


This articulation agreement displays the lower-division courses required in the major: Sacramento State courses on the left and approved (articulated) transfer courses on the right. Although completion of the coursework listed below is not mandatory prior to admission, students are advised to complete as much lower-division course preparation as possible prior to transfer.


Additional Resources:

  • See the University Catalog for the full listing of degree requirements for this major.
  • Visit our Sac State Apply page for more information about our campus!
  • Visit the Admissions website for current transfer admission requirements.
  • Connect with an Admissions Counselor.

requirement.name: Courses approved for Second Semester Composition Graduation Requirement

templateAssets.content:
1. Students must earn a "C-" grade or higher in all courses and prerequisite courses required in the major, with the exception of CHEM 1A, which requires a "C" grade or higher.
  2. The Associate Degree for Transfer (ADT) in Chemistry is compatible with the B.S. in Chemistry at Sacramento State. Students pursuing the Associate Degree for Transfer must complete all lower-division major coursework with a "C" or better.
  3. Students pursuing a Chemistry degree are strongly encouraged to complete as much of the lower-division science and math curriculum as possible. In particular, the department advises Chemistry majors to complete: CHEM 1A, CHEM 1B, MATH 30, MATH 31, MATH 32, PHYS 11A, PHYS 11B, and PHYS 11C prior to transfer.
  4. Students are strongly advised to complete Calculus and Physics prior to transfer as these courses are prerequisites to Physical Chemistry (a required upper-division course for all Chemistry majors).
  5. PHYS 11A, 11B and 11C are required for the B.S. in Chemistry.
  6. English 20, or an approved second semester composition course, is a prerequisite for all upper-division laboratories. It is recommended students complete this course prior to transfer.
  7. ﻿Foreign Language Graduation Requirement Exemption: Students graduating with a B.S. in Chemistry will not be subject to the University’s Foreign Language Graduation Requirement. Students who change major may be subject to the University’s Foreign Language Graduation Requirement.
  8. For additional information, please visit: Department of Chemistry.
